<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Grindelia stricta </i>is a perennial glandular composite with showy, yellow flowers. Plants have a woody caudex and grow along Californiaâ€™s coastline. <i>G. stricta</i>var. <i>platyphylla </i> has the widest range, occurring from Los Angeles County north to Del Norte County. <i>G. stricta</i>var. <i>stricta </i>grows along the Northern California Coast (263A), while <i>G. stricta</i>var. <i>angustifolia </i>is a Central California Coast (261A) plant.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Grindelia camporum</i> stands found in non-tidal environments in the Great Valley have been placed in the <i>Bidens cernua - Euthamia occidentalis - Ludwigia palustris</i> Alliance. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands at Suisun Marsh (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000) and at Point Reyes <i>Juncus arcticus</i> or occur adjacent to more low-lying stands of <i>Sarcocornia pacifica</i>. Stands in the Sacramento - San Joaquin River delta (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007) have <i>Distichlis spicata</i>, and they are classified as part of <i>Distichlis spicata </i>alliance. Many of these stands have been subjected to cattle grazing. Stands observed at Stone Lagoon in Humboldt Co. associate with <i>D. spicata </i>stands on coastal dunes. Other species of <i>Grindelia </i>appear to occur in similar settings as <i>G. stricta </i>in California. We need more sampling and analysis to clarify <i>Grindelia </i>stands in overall coastal salt marsh, alkaline marsh, and grassland patterns. </div>
</div>

	

    
